statement:
Consider the vectors

\begin{align*}v_1 = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1/2 \\ 1/2 \\ 1/2 \\ 1/2
\end{array}\right), \quad 
v_2 = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1/2 \\ 1/2 \\ -1/2 \\ -1/2
\end{array}\right),\end{align*}

\begin{align*}v_3 = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1/2 \\ -1/2 \\ 1/2 \\ -1/2
\end{array}\right), \quad 
v_4 = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1/2 \\ -1/2 \\ -1/2 \\ 1/2
\end{array}\right)\end{align*}

\textbf{a)} Check that \emph{v\textsubscript{1}, v\textsubscript{2},
v\textsubscript{3}, v\textsubscript{4}} is an orthogonal basis of
\textbf{R}\textsuperscript{4}.
